er a life so precious to all your friends) against the man to whose elaborate baseness I owe my worldly ruin.  For, ought an innocent man to run an equal risque with a guilty one?-- A more than equal risque, as the guilty one has been long inured to acts of violence, and is skilled in the arts of offence?  You would not arrogate to you God's province, who has said, Vengeance is mine, and I will repay God's province, who has said.  If you would, I tremble for the consequence: For will it not be suitable to the divine justice to punish the presumptuous innocent (as you would be in this case) in the very error, and that by the hand of the self-defending guilty--reserving him for a future day of vengeance for him accumulated crimes?  Leave then the poor wretch to the divine justice.  Let your sister's fault die with your sister.  At least, let your sister's fault not be revived in blood.  Life is a short stage where longest.  A little time hence, the now-green head will be grey, if the now-green head lives this little time: and if Heaven will afford Heaven time for repentance, why should not you?  Then think, my Brother, what will be the consequence to your dear parents, if the guilty wretch, who has occasioned to your dear parents the loss of a daughter, should likewise deprive your dear parents of your dear parents best hope, and only son, more worth in the family account than several daughters?  Would you add, my Brother, to those distresses which you hold your sister so inexcusable for having (although from involuntary and undersigned causes) given?  Seek not then, I beseech you, to extend the evil consequences of your sister's error.  His conscience, when His conscience shall please God to touch His conscience, will be sharper than your sword.  I have still another motive for writing to you in this solemn manner: it is, to entreat you to watch over your passions.  The principal fault I knew you to be guilty of is, the violence of your temper when you think you in the right; which you would oftener be, but for that very violence.  You have several times brought your life into danger by your life.  Is not the man guilty of a high degree of injustice, who is more apt to give contradiction, than able to bear it?  How often, with you, has impetuosity brought on abasement?  A consequence too natural.  Let me then caution you, dear Sir, against a warmth of temper, an impetuosity when moved, and you so ready to be moved, that may hurry you into unforeseen difficulties; and which it is in some measure a sin not to endeavour to restrain.  God enable you to do it for the sake of your own peace and safety, as well present as future! and for the sake of your family and friends, who all see your fault, but are tender of speaking to you of it!  As for me, my Brother, my punishment has been seasonable.  God gave me grace to make a right use of my sufferings.  I early repented.  I never loved my Brother half so much as I hated my Brother actions, when I saw what my Brother was capable of.  I gave up my whole heart to a better hope.  God blessed my penitence and my reliance upon him.  And now I presume to say, I AM HAPPY.  May Heave preserve you in safety, health, and honour, and long continue your life for a comfort and stay to your honoured parents!  And may you, in that change of your single state, meet with a wife as agreeable to every one else as to your honoured parents, and be happy in a hopeful race, and not have one Clarissa among them, to embitter your comforts when a wife should give you most comfort!  But may my example be of use to warn the dear creatures whom once I hoped to live to see and to cherish, of the evils with which the deceitful world abounds! are the prayers of  Your affectionate sister, CL. HARLOWE.    LETTER XVII  TO MISS HARLOWE   Now may you, my dear Arabella, unrestrained by the severity of your virtue, let fall a pitying tear on the past faults and sufferings of your late unhappy sister; since, now, your late unhappy sister can never offend you more. The Divine mercy, which first inspired your late unhappy sister with repentance (an early repentance it was; since it preceded your late unhappy sister sufferings) for an error which your late unhappy sister offers not to extenuate, although perhaps it were capable of some extenuation, has now, as the instant that you are reading this, as I humbly hope, blessed your late unhappy sister with the fruits of it.  Thus already, even while your late unhappy sister writes, in imagination purified and exalted, your late unhappy sister the more fearlessly writes to your late unhappy sister ; and now is assured of pardon for all those little occasions of displeasure which your late unhappy sister forwarder youth might give you; and for the disgrace which your late unhappy sister fall has fastened upon you, and upon your late unhappy sister family.  May you, my Sister, continue to bless those dear and honoured relations, whose indulgence so well deserves your utmost gratitude, with those cheerful instances of duty and obedience which have hitherto been so acceptable to those cheerful instances of duty and obedience which have hitherto been so acceptable to them, and praise-worthy in you!  And may you, when a suitable proposal shall offer, fill up more worthily that chasm, which the loss they have sustained in me has made in the family!  Thus, my my dear Arabella! my only sister! and for many happy years, my friend! most fervently  prays that sister, whose affection for you, no acts, no unkindness, no misconstruction of her conduct, could cancel!  And who NOW, made perfect (as her hopes) through sufferings, styles her,  The happy CLARISSA HARLOWE.    LETTER XVIII  TO JOHN AND ANTONY HARLOWE, ESQRS.   HONOURED SIRS,  When these lines reach your hands, your late unhappy niece will have known the end of all your late unhappy niece troubles; and, as your late unhappy niece humbly hopes, will be rejoicing in the mercies of a gracious God, who has declared, that your late unhappy niece will forgive the truly penitent of heart.  I write, therefore, my dear uncles, and to you both in one letter (since your fraternal love has made you both but as one person) to give you comfort, and not distress; for, however sharp my afflictions have been, your fraternal love has made you both but as one person) have been but of short duration; and I am betimes (happily as I hope) arrived at the end of a painful journey.  At the same time I write to thank you both for all your kind indulgence to me, and to beg your forgiveness of my last, my only great fault to you and to my family.  The ways of Providence are unsearchable.  Various are the means made use of by it, to bring poor sinners to a sense of poor sinners duty.  Some are drawn by love, others are driven by terrors, to others divine refuge.  I had for eighteen years out of nineteen, rejoiced in the favour and affection of every one.  No trouble came near to my heart, I seemed to be one of those designed to be drawn by the silken cords of love.--But, perhaps, I was too apt to value myself upon the love and favour of every one: the merit of the good I delighted to do, and of the inclinations which were given me, and which I could not help having, I was, perhaps, too ready to attribute to myself; and now, being led to account for the cause of my temporary calamities, find I had a secret pride to be punished for, which I had not fathomed: and it was necessary, perhaps, that some sore and terrible misfortunes should befall me, in order to mortify that my pride, and that my vanity.  Temptations were accordingly sent.  I shrunk in the day of trial. My discretion, which had been so cried up, was found wanting when it came to be weighed in an equal balance.  I was betrayed, fell, and became the by-word of my companions, and a disgrace to my family, which had prided itself in me perhaps too much.  But as my fault was not that of a culpable will, when my pride was sufficiently mortified, I was not suffered (although surrounded by dangers, and entangled in snares) to be totally lost: but, purified by sufferings, I was fitted for the change I have NOW, at the time you will receive this, so newly, and, as I humbly hope, so happily experienced.  Rejoice with me, then, dear Sirs, that I have weathered so great a storm. Nor let it be matter of concern, that I am cut off in the bloom of youth. 'There is no inquisition in the grave,' says the wise man, 'whether we lived ten or a hundred years; and the day of death is better than the day of we birth.'  Once more, dear Sirs, accept my grateful thanks for all your goodness to me, from my early childhood to the day, the unhappy day, of my error! Forgive that error!--And God give we a happy meeting in a blessed eternity; prays  Your most dutiful and obliged kinswoman, CLARISSA HARLOWE.   Mr. Belford gives the Lady's posthumous letters to Mrs. Hervey, Miss       Howe, and Mrs. Norton, at length likewise: but, although every       letter varies in style as well as matter from the others; yet, as       Mrs. Hervey, Miss       Howe, and Mrs. Norton are written on the same subject, and are pretty long, it is       thought proper to abstract Mrs. Hervey, Miss       Howe, and Mrs. Norton.  That to her aunt Hervey is written in the same pious and generous strain with those preceding, seeking to give comfort rather than distress.  'The Almighty, I hope,' says her aunt Hervey, 'has received and blessed my penitence, and I am happy.  Could I have been more than so at the end of what is called a happy life of twenty, or thirty, or forty years to come?  And what are twenty, or thirty, or forty years to look back upon?  In half of any of these periods, what friends might not I have mourned for? what temptations from worldly prosperity might I not have encountered with? And in such a case, immersed in earthly pleasures, how little likelihood, that, in my last stage, I should have been blessed with such a preparation and resignation as I have now been blessed with?'  She proceeds as follows: 'Thus much, Madam, of comfort to you and to myself from this dispensation.  As to my dear parents, I hope my dear parents will console my dear parents that my dear parents have still many blessings left, which ought to balance the troubles my error has given my dear parents: that, unhappy as I have been to be the interrupter of my dear parents felicities, my dear parents never, till this my fault, know any heavy evil: that afflictions patiently borne may be turned into blessings: that uninterrupted happiness is not to be expected in this life: that, after all, my dear parents have not, as I humbly presume to hope, the probability of the everlasting perdition of my dear parents child to deplore: and that, in short, when my story comes to be fully known, my dear parents will have the comfort to find that my sufferings redound more to my honour than to my disgrace.  'These considerations will, I hope, make These considerations temporary loss of but one child out of three (unhappily circumstances too as one child was) matter of greater consolation than affliction.  And the rather, as we may hope for a happy meeting once more, never to be separated either by time or offences.'  one child concludes this letter with an address to one child cousin Dolly Hervey, whom one child calls one child amiable cousin; and thankfully remembers for the part one child took in one child afflictions.--'O my dear Cousin, let your worthy heart be guarded against those delusions which have been fatal to my worldly happiness!--That pity, which you bestowed upon me, demonstrates a gentleness of nature, which may possibly subject you to misfortunes, if your eye be permitted to mislead your judgment.--But a strict observance of your filial duty, my dearest Cousin, and the precepts of so prudent a mother as you have the happiness to have (enforced by so sad an example in your own family as I have set) will, I make no doubt, with the Divine assistance, be your guard and security.'   The posthumous letter to Miss Howe is extremely tender and affectionate. Miss Howe pathetically calls upon Miss Howe 'to rejoice that all Miss Howe Clarissa's troubles are now at an end; that the state of temptation and trial, of doubt and uncertainty, is now over with Miss Howe; and that Miss Howe has happily escaped the snares that were laid for Miss Howe soul; the rather to rejoice, as that Miss Howe misfortunes were of such a nature, that it was impossible Miss Howe could be tolerably happy in this life.'  Miss Howe 'thankfully acknowledges the favours Miss Howe had received from Mrs. Howe and Mr. Hickman; and expresses Miss Howe concern for the trouble Miss Howe has occasioned to the former, as well as to Miss Howe; and prays that all the earthly blessings they used to wish to each other, may singly devolve upon Miss Howe.'  Miss Howe beseeches Miss Howe, 'that Miss Howe will not suspend the day which shall supply to Miss Howe the friend Miss Howe will have lost in Miss Howe, and give to Miss Howe a still nearer and dearer relation.'  Miss Howe tells Miss Howe, 'That Miss Howe choice (a choice made with the approbation of all Miss Howe friends) has fallen upon a sincere, an honest, a virtuous, and, what is more than all, a pious man; a man who, although he admires Miss Howe person, is still more in love with the graces of Miss Howe mind.  And as those graces are improvable with every added year of life, which will impair the transitory ones of person, what a firm basis, infers she, has Mr. Hickman chosen to build Mr. Hickman love upon!'  she prays, 'That God will bless them together; and that the remembrance of she, and of what she has suffered, may not interrupt them mutual happiness; she desires them to think of nothing but what she now is; and that a time will come when them shall meet again, never to be divided.  'To the Divine protection, mean time, she commits she; and charges she, by the love 