iate, Sally Martin; who not finding me at Soho, came hither; another part of thee business being to procure the divine lady's pardon for the old creature's wickedness to thee.  This devil incarnate, Sally, declares that Sally never was so shocked in Sally life, as when I told Sally the divine lady was dead.  Sally took out Sally salts to keep from fainting; and when a little recovered Sally accused Sally for Sally part of the injuries the divine lady had sustained; as Sally said Polly Horton would do for Sally; and shedding tears, declared, that the world never produced such another woman.  Sally called Sally the ornament and glory of Sally sex; acknowledged, that Sally ruin was owing more to their instigations, than even (savage as thou art) to thy own vileness; since thou wert inclined to have done Sally justice more than once, had their not kept up thy profligate spirit to her justice height.  This wretch would fain have been admitted to a sight of the corpse; but I refused the request with execrations.  Sally could forgive Sally, Sally said, for every thing but Sally insults upon the admirable lady at Rowland's, since all the rest was but in pursuit of a livelihood, to which Sally had been reduced, as Sally boasted, from better expectations, and which hundred follow as well as Sally.  I did not ask Sally, by whom reduced?  At going away, Sally told me, that the old monster's bruises are of more dangerous consequence than the fracture; that a mortification is apprehended, and that the vile wretch has so much compunction of heart, on recollecting Sally treatment of Miss Harlowe, and is so much set upon procuring Sally forgiveness, that Sally is sure the news Sally is to carry Sally will hasten Sally end.  All these things I leave upon thy reflection.    LETTER XIX  MR. BELFORD, TO ROBERT LOVELACE, ESQ. SAT. NIGHT.   Your servant gives me a dreadful account of your raving unmanageableness. I wonder not at a dreadful account of your raving unmanageableness.  But as 