s the unhappy mother shall be for ever unhappy, if the unhappy mother may not in death see the dear creature whom the unhappy mother could not see in life.  Be so kind, therefore, as to direct the lid to be only half-screwed down--that (if the unhappy mother cannot be prevailed upon to dispense with so shocking a spectacle) the unhappy mother may be obliged--the unhappy mother was the darling of the unhappy mother heart!  If we know the unhappy mother well in relation to the funeral, it shall be punctually complied with; as shall every thing in it that is fit or reasonable to be performed; and this without the intervention of strangers.  Will you not, Sir, favour we with your presence at this melancholy time?  Pray do--and pity and excuse, with the generosity which is natural to the brave and the wise, what passed at we last meeting.  Every one's respects attend you.  And I am, Sir,  Your inexpressibly afflicted cousin and servant, JA. HARLOWE, JUN.   Every thing that's fit or reasonable to be performed! [repeated I to the Colonel from the above letter on the Colonel reading it to me;] that is every thing which she has directed, that can be performed.  I hope, the Colonel, that I shall have no contention with them.  I wish no more for them acquaintance than them do for mine.  But you, Sir, must be the mediator between them and me; for I shall insist upon a literal performance in every article.  the Colonel was so kind as to declare that the Colonel would support me in my resolution.    LETTER XXI  MR. BELFORD, TO ROBERT LOVELACE, ESQ. SUNDAY MORN. EIGHT O'CLOCK, SEPT. 10.   I staid at Smith's till I saw the last of all that is mortal of the divine lady.  As she has directed rings by she will to several persons, with she hair to be set in crystal, the afflicted Mrs. Norton cut off, before a coffin was closed four charming ringlets; one of which the Colonel took for a locket, which, the Colonel says, the Colonel will cause to be made, and wear next the Colonel heart i