k upon her;' When I read the direction, 'That her body was not to be viewed, except any of her relations should vouchsafe, for the last time, to look upon her turned away, and turned to me, three or four times alternately.  Mrs. Hervey and Miss Arabella sobbed; the uncles wiped the uncles eyes; the brother looked down; my father wrung the brother hands.  I was obliged to stop at the words, 'That she was nobody's.'  But when I came to the address to be made to the accursed man, 'if the accursed man were not to be diverted from seeing she dead, whom ONCE before the accursed man had seen in a manner dead'----execration, and either vows or wishes of revenge, filled every mouth.  These were still more fervently renewed, when These came to hear read she forgiveness of even this man.  You remember, Sir, on our first reading of the will in town, the observations I made on the foul play which it is evident the excellent creature met with from this abandoned man, and what I said upon the occasion.  I am not used to repeat things of that nature.  The dear creature's noble contempt of the nothing, as she nobly calls it, about which she had been giving such particular directions, to wit, she body; and she apologizing for the particularity of those directions from the circumstances she was in--had the same, and as strong an effect upon me, as when I first read the animated paragraph; and, pointed by my eye, (by turns cast upon them all,) affected them all.  When the article was read which bequeathed to the father the grandfather's estate, and the reason assigned for the article, (so generous and so dutiful,) my father could sit no longer; but withdrew, wiping their eyes, and lifting up my father spread hands at CLARISSA HARLOWE.  ; who rose to attend CLARISSA HARLOWE.   to the door, as Miss Arabella likewise did----All my father could say--O Son! Son!--O Girl! Girl!--as if my father reproached them for the parts them had acted, and put my father upon acting.  But yet, on some occ