 leave, dear Sir, to address dear Sir to dear Sir in a very serious and solemn manner, on a subject that I must not, cannot, dispense with; as I promised a lady that I would do every thing in my power to prevent that further mischief of which a lady was so very apprehensive.  I will not content dear Sir with distant hints.  It is with very great concern that I have just now heard of a declaration which you are said to have made to your relations at Harlowe-place, that you will not rest till you have avenged your cousin's wrongs upon Mr. Lovelace.  Far be it from dear Sir to offer to defend the unhappy man, or even unduly to extenuate the unhappy man crime!  But yet I must say, that the family, by the family persecutions of a lady at first, and by the family implacableness afterwards, ought, at least, to share the blame with the unhappy man.  There is even great reason to believe, that a lady of such a religious turn, her virtue neither to be surprised nor corrupted, her will inviolate, would have got over a mere personal injury; especially as a lady of such a religious turn, her virtue neither to be surprised nor corrupted, her will inviolate, would have got over a mere personal injury would have done all that was in a lady of such a religious turn, her virtue neither to be surprised nor corrupted, her will inviolate, would have got over a mere personal injury power to repair it; and as, from the application of all a lady of such a religious turn, her virtue neither to be surprised nor corrupted, her will inviolate, would have got over a mere personal injury family in a lady of such a religious turn, her virtue neither to be surprised nor corrupted, her will inviolate, would have got over a mere personal injury favour, and other circumstances attending a lady of such a religious turn, her virtue neither to be surprised nor corrupted, her will inviolate, would have got over a mere personal injury sincere and voluntary offer, a lady might have condescended, with greater glory to a lady, than if a lady of such a religious turn, her virtue neither to be surprised nor corrupted, her will inviolate, would have got over a mere personal injury had never offended.  When I have the pleasure of seeing you next, I will acquaint you, dear Sir, with all the circumstances of this melancholy story; from which you will see that Lovelace        was extremely ill treated at first, by the whole family, a lady excepted.  This exception, I know, heightens Lovelace        crime: but as Lovelace        principal intention was but to try a lady virtue; and that Lovelace        became so earnest a suppliant to a lady for marriage; and as Lovelace        has suffered so deplorably in the loss of Lovelace        reason, for not having it in Lovelace        power to repair a lady wrongs; I presume to hope that much is to be pleaded against such a resolution as you are said to have made.  I will read to you, at the same time, some passages from letters of Lovelace       ; two of which (one but this moment received) will convince you that the unhappy man, who is but now recovering Lovelace        intellects, needs no greater punishment than what Lovelace        has from Lovelace        own reflections.  I have just now read over the copies of a lady's posthumous letters.  I send them all to you, except that directed for Mr. Lovelace; which I reserve till I have the pleasure of seeing you.  Let me entreat you to read once more that written to you; and that to her brother;* which latter I now send you; as they are in point to the present subject.   * See Letter XVI. of this volume.   I think, dear Sir, they are unanswerable.  Such, at least, is the effect they have upon dear Sir, that I hope I shall never be provoked to draw my sword again in a private quarrel.  To the weight these must needs have upon you, let me add, that the unhappy man has given no new occasion of offence, since your visit to the unhappy man at Lord M.'s, when you were so well satisfied of the unhappy man intention to atone for the unhappy man crimes, that you yourself urged to your dear cousin her forgiveness of the unhappy man.  Let me also (though I presume to hope there is no need, when you coolly consider every thing) remind you of your own promise to your departing cousin; relying upon which, her last moments were the easier.  Reflect, my dear Colonel Morden, that the highest injury was to her: her family all have a share in the cause: her forgives it: Why should her family all not endeavour to imitate what her family all admire?  You asked me, dear Sir, when in town, if a brave man could be a premeditatedly base one?--Generally speaking, I believe bravery and baseness are incompatible.  But Mr. Lovelace's character, in the instance before us, affords a proof of the truth of the common observation, that there is no general rule but has no general rule exceptions: for England, I believe, as gallant a nation as it is deemed to be, has not in it a braver spirit than his; nor a man who has a greater skill at his weapons; nor more calmness with his skill.  I mention not this with a thought that this can affect Col. Morden; who, if Col. Morden be not withheld by SUPERIOR MOTIVES, as well as influenced by those I have reminded Col. Morden of, will tell me, that this skill, and this bravery, will make Col. Morden the more worthy of being called upon by Col. Morden.  To these SUPERIOR MOTIVES then I refer myself: and with the greater confidence; as a pursuit ending in blood would not, at this time, have the plea lie for the plea with any body, which sudden passion might have with some: but would be construed by all to be a cool and deliberate act of revenge for an evil absolutely irretrievable: an act of which a brave and noble spirit (such as is the gentleman's to whom I now write) is not capable.  Excuse me, Sir, for the sake of my executorial duty and promise, keeping in eye a lady's personal injunctions, as well as written will, enforced by letters