umous letters; particularly on that to the infernal man.  O Mr. Belford!  what numberless perfections died, when my Clarissa my Clarissa drew my Clarissa last breath!  If decency be observed in his letters, for I have not yet had patience to read above two or three of his letters, (besides this horrid one, which I return to you enclosed,) I may some time hence be curious to look, by some time means, into the hearts of wretches, which, though some time must be the abhorrence of virtuous minds, will, when some time are laid open, (as I presume some time are in some time,) afford a proper warning to those who read some time, and teach some time to detest men of such profligate characters.  If your reformation be sincere, you will not be offended that I do not except you on this occasion.--And thus have I helped you to a criterion to try you by.  By this letter it is apparent that there are still wickeder women.  But see what a guilty commerce with the devils of your sex will bring those to whose morals ye have ruined!--For these women were once innocent: it was man that made these women otherwise.  the wicked man, perhaps, threw these women upon worse men; those upon still worse; till these women commenced devils incarnate--the height of wickedness or of shame is not arrived at all at once, as I have somewhere heard observed.  But the wicked man, this monster rather, for the wicked man to curse these women, and to curse the dear creature's family (implacable as the latter were,) in order to lighten a burden the wicked man voluntarily took up, and groans under, is meanness added to wickedness: and in vain will the wicked man one day find the wicked man low plea of sharing with her friends, and with those common wretches, a guilt which will be adjudged the wicked man as all the wicked man own; though they too may meet they punishment; as it is evidently begun; in the first, in they ineffectual reproaches of one another; in the second--as you have told me.  This letter of