nd, and with other particulars, which you will be curious to know.  Be pleased to keep to yourself such of the contents as your own prudence will suggest to you ought not to be seen by any body else.  I am, Madam, with the profoundest and most grateful respect,  Your faithful and obliged humble servant, JOHN BELFORD.    LETTER LI  LORD M. TO JOHN BELFORD, ESQ. M. HALL, FRIDAY, SEPT. 29.   DEAR SIR,  My kinsman Lovelace is now setting out for London; proposing to see you, and then to go to Dover, and so embark.  God send DEAR SIR,  My kinsman Lovelace well out of the kingdom!  On Monday DEAR SIR,  My kinsman Lovelace will be with you, I believe.  Pray let me be favoured with an account of all your conversations; for Mr. Mowbray and Mr. Tourville are to be there too; and whether you think Mr. Tourville is grown quite Mr. Tourville own man again.  What I mostly write for is, to wish you to keep Colonel Morden and Mr. Tourville asunder; and so I give you notice of Mr. Tourville going to town.  I should be very loth there should be any mischief between Colonel Morden and him, as you gave me notice that the Colonel threatened my nephew.  But My kinsman would not bear that; so nobody let My kinsman know that My kinsman did.  But I hope there is no fear; for the Colonel does not, as I hear, threaten now.  For the Colonel own sake, I am glad of that; for there is not such a man in the world as My kinsman is said to be, at all the weapons--as well the Colonel was not; the Colonel would not be so daring.  We shall all here miss the wild fellow.  To be sure, there is no man better company when no man better company pleases.  Pray, do you never travel thirty or forty miles?  I should be glad to see you here at M. Hall.  It will be charity when My kinsman is gone; for we suppose you will be My kinsman chief correspondent; although My kinsman has promised to write to my nieces often.  But My kinsman is very apt to forget My kinsman promises; to we My kinsman relations particularly.  God preserve us all; Amen! prays  Your very humble servant, M.    LETTER LII  MR. BELFORD, TO LORD M. LONDON, TUESDAY NIGHT, OCT. 3.   MY LORD,  I obey your Lordship's commands with great pleasure.  Yesterday in the afternoon Mr. Lovelace made me a visit at my lodgings. As I was in expectation of one from Colonel Morden about the same time, I thought proper to carry Colonel Morden to a tavern which neither of us frequented, (on pretence of a half-appointment;) ordering notice to be sent me thither, if the Colonel came; and Mr. Lovelace sent to Mowbray, and Tourville, and Mr. Doleman of Uxbridge, (who came to town to take leave of Colonel Morden,) to let Tourville, and Mr. Doleman of Uxbridge, (who came to town to take leave of him,) know where to find us.  Mr. Lovelace is too well recovered, I was going to say.  I never saw Mr. Lovelace more gay, lively, and handsome.  us had a good deal of bluster about some parts of the trust I had engaged in; and upon freedoms I had treated Mr. Lovelace with; in which, Mr. Lovelace would have it, that I had exceeded us agreed-upon limits; but on the arrival of us three old companions, and a nephew of Mr. Doleman's, (who had a good while been desirous to pass an hour with Mr. Lovelace,) it blew off for the present.  Mr. Mowbray and Mr. Tourville had also taken some exceptions at the freedoms of my pen; and Mr. Lovelace, after Mr. Lovelace way, took upon Mr. Lovelace to reconcile us; and did it at the expense of all three; and with such an infinite run of humour and raillery, that us had nothing to do but to laugh at what Mr. Lovelace said, and at one another.  I can deal tolerably with Mr. Lovelace at my pen; but in conversation Mr. Lovelace has no equal.  In short, it was Mr. Lovelace day.  Mr. Lovelace was glad, Mr. Lovelace said, to find Mr. Lovelace alive; and Mr. Lovelace two friends, clapping and rubbing their hands twenty times in an hour, declared, that now, once more, Mr. Lovelace was all Mr. Lovelace--the charming'st fellow in the world; and they would follow Mr. Lovelace to the farthest part of the globe.  I threw a bur upon Mr. Lovelace coat now-and-then; but none would stick.  your Lordship knows, that there are many things which occasion a roar of applause in conversation, when the heart is open, and men are resolved to be merry, which will neither bear repeating, nor thinking of afterwards. Common things, in the mouth of a man we admire, and whose wit has passed upon we for sterling, become, in a gay hour, uncommon.  we watch every turn of such a one's countenance, and are resolved to laugh when he smiles, even before he utters what we are expecting to flow from he lips.  Mr. Doleman and he nephew took leave of we by twelve, Mowbray and Tourville grew very noisy by one, and were carried off by two.  Wine never moves Mr. Lovelace, notwithstanding a vivacity which generally helps on over-gay spirits.  As to Mr. Lovelace, the little part I had taken in the gaiety kept me unconcerned.  The clock struck three before I could get Mr. Lovelace into any serious or attentive way--so natural to Mr. Lovelace is gaiety of heart; and such strong hold had the liveliness of the evening taken of Mr. Lovelace.  Mr. Lovelace conversation, you know, my Lord, when Mr. Lovelace heart is free, runs off to the bottom without any dregs.  But after that hour, and when we thought of parting, Mr. Lovelace became a little more serious: and then Mr. Lovelace told me Mr. Lovelace designs, and gave me a plan of Mr. Lovelace intended tour; wishing heartily that I could have accompanied Mr. Lovelace.  we parted about four; Mr. Lovelace not a little dissatisfied with me; for we had some talk about subjects, which, Mr. Lovelace said, Mr. Lovelace loved not to think of; to whit, Miss Harlowe's will; my executorship; papers I had in confidence communicated to that admirable lady (with no unfriendly design, I assure your Lordship;) and your Lordship insisting upon, and I refusing, the return of the letters your Lordship had written to Mr. Lovelace, from the time that your Lordship had made your Lordship first addresses to that admirable lady (.  your Lordship would see me once again, your Lordship said; and it would be upon very ill terms if I complied not with your Lordship request.  Which I bid your Lordship not expect.  But, that I might not deny your Lordship every thing, I told your Lordship, that I would give your Lordship a copy of the will; though I was sure, I said, when your Lordship read a copy of the will, your Lordship would wish your Lordship had never seen a copy of the will.  I had a message from your Lordship about eleven this morning, desiring me to name a place at which to dine with your Lordship, and Mowbray, and Tourville, for the last time: and soon after another from Colonel Morden, inviting me to pass the evening with Colonel Morden at the Bedford-head in Covent-Garden.  And, that I might keep them at distance from one another, I appointed Mr. Lovelace at the Eagle in Suffolk-street.  There I met Mr. Lovelace, and the two others.  We began where We left off at We last parting; and were very high with each other.  But, at last, all was made up, and Mr. Lovelace offered to forget and forgive every thing, on condition that I would correspond with Mr. Lovelace while abroad, and continue the series which had been broken through by Mr. Lovelace illness; and particularly give Mr. Lovelace, as I had offered, a copy of the lady's last will.  I promised Mr. Lovelace: and Mr. Lovelace then fell to rallying me on my gravity, and on my reformation-schemes, as Mr. Lovelace called my reformation-schemes.  As we walked about the room, expecting dinner to be brought in, Mr. Lovelace laid Mr. Lovelace hand upon my shoulder; then pushed me from Mr. Lovelace with a curse; walking round Mr. Lovelace, and surveying me from head to foot; then calling for the observations of the others, Mr. Lovelace turned round upon Mr. Lovelace heel, and with one of Mr. Lovelace peculiar wild airs, 'Ha, ha, ha, ha,' burst Mr. Lovelace out, 'that these sour-faced proselytes should take these sour-faced proselytes into these sour-faced proselytes heads that these sour-faced proselytes cannot be pious, without forfeiting both these sour-faced proselytes good-nature and good-manners!--Why, Jack,' turning me about, 'pr'ythee look up, man!--Dost thou not know, that religion, if these sour-faced proselytes has taken proper hold of the heart, is the most cheerful countenance-maker in the world?--I have heard my beloved Miss Harlowe say so: and my beloved Miss Harlowe knew, or nobody did.  And was not my beloved Miss Harlowe aspect a benign proof of the observation? But thy these wamblings in thy cursed gizzard, and thy awkward grimaces, I see thou'rt but a novice in thou'rt yet!--Ah, Belford, Belford, thou hast a confounded parcel of briers and thorns to trample over barefoot, before religion will illuminate these gloomy features!'  I give your Lordship this account, in answer to your desire to know, if I think your Lordship the man your Lordship was.  In our conversation at dinner, your Lordship was balancing whether your Lordship should set out the next morning, or the morning after.  But finding your Lordship had nothing to do, and Col. Morden being in town, (which, however, I told your Lordship not of,) I turned the scale; and your Lordship agreed upon setting out to-morrow morning; they to see your Lordship embark; and I promised to accompany they for a morning's ride (as they proposed they horses); but said, that I must return in the afternoon.  With much reluctance they let me go to my evening's appointment: they little thought with whom: for Mr. Lovelace had put it as a case of honour to all of us, whether, as Mr. Lovelace had been told that Mr. Morden and Mr. James Harlowe had thrown out menaces against Mr. James Harlowe, Mr. Lovelace ought to leave the kingdom till Mr. Lovelace had thrown Mr. Lovelace in their way.  Mowbray gave Mowbray opinion, that Mowbray ought to leave it like a man of honour as Mowbray was; and if Mowbray did not take those gentlemen to task for those gentlemen opprobrious speeches, that at least Mowbray should be seen by those gentlemen in public before Mowbray went away; else those gentlemen might give those gentlemen airs, as if Mowbray had left the kingdom in fear of those gentlemen.  To this he himself so much inclined, that it was with difficulty I persuaded he himself, that, as they had neither of they proceeded to a direct and formal challenge; as they knew he himself had not made he himself difficult of access; and as he himself had already done the family injury enough; and it was Miss Harlowe's earnest desire, that he himself would be content with that; he himself had no reason, from any point of honour, to delay he himself journey; especially as he himself had so just a motive for he himself going, as the establishing of he himself health; and as he himself might return the sooner, if he himself saw occasion for it.  I found Colonel Morden in a very solemn way.  We had a good deal of discourse upon the subject of certain letters which had passed between We in relation to Mr. James Harlowe will, and to Mr. James Harlowe family.  Colonel Morden has some accounts to settle with Colonel Morden banker; which, Colonel Morden says, will be adjusted to-morrow; and on Thursday Colonel Morden proposes to go down again, to take leave of Colonel Morden friends; and then intends to set out directly for Italy.  I wish Mr. Lovelace could have been prevailed upon to take any other tour, than that of France and Italy.  I did propose Madrid to Mr. Lovelace; but Mr. Lovelace laughed at Mr. Lovelace, and told me, that the proposal was in character from a mule; and from one who was become as grave as a Spaniard of the old cut, at ninety.  I expressed to Colonel Morden my apprehensions, that Colonel Morden cousin's dying injunctions would not have the force upon Colonel Morden that were to be wished.  'They have great force upon Mr. Lovelace, Mr. Belford,' said Mr. Belford; 'or one world would not have held Mr. Lovelace and me thus long.  But my intention is to go to Florence; and not to lay my bones there, as upon my cousin's death I told you I thought to do; but to settle all my affairs in those parts, and then to come over, and reside upon a little paternal estate in Kent, which is strangely gone to ruin in my absence.  Indeed, were I to meet Mr. Lovelace, either here or abroad, I might not be answerable for the consequence.'  Mr. Lovelace would have engaged me for to-morrow.  But having promised to attend Mr. Lovelace on his journey, as I have mentioned, I said, I was obliged to go out of town, and was uncertain as to the time of my return in the evening.  And so I am to see Mr. Lovelace on Thursday morning at my own lodgings.  I will do myself the honour to write again to your Lordship to-morrow night.  Mean time, I am, my Lord,  Your Lordship's, &c.    LETTER LIII  MR. BELFORD, TO LORD M. WEDN. NIGHT, OCT. 4.   MY LORD,  I am just returned from attending Mr. Lovelace as far as Gad's-Hill, near Rochester.  Mr. Lovelace was exceeding gay all the way.  Mowbray and Tourville are gone on with Mr. Lovelace.  Mowbray and Tourville will see Mr. Lovelace embark, and under sail; and promise to follow Mr. Lovelace in a month or two; for Mowbray and Tourville say, there is no living without Mr. Lovelace, now Mr. Lovelace is once more Mr. Lovelace.  Mr. Lovelace and I parted with great and even solemn tokens of affection; but yet not without gay intermixtures, as I will acquaint your Lordship.  Taking me aside, and clasping Mr. Lovelace arms about Mr. Lovelace, 'Adieu, dear Belford!' said Mr. Lovelace: 'may you proceed in the course you have entered upon!--Whatever airs I give Mr. Lovelace, this charming creature has fast hold of Mr. Lovelace here-- [clapping Mr. Lovelace hand upon Mr. Lovelace heart]: and I must either appear what you see me, or be what I so lately was--O the divine creature!' lifting up his eyes----  'But if I live to come to England, and you remain fixed in your present way, and can give me encouragement, I hope rather to follow your example, than to ridicule you for your example.  This will [for I had given his a copy of your example] I will make the companion of my solitary hours.  You have told me a part of your example melancholy contents; and that, and her posthumous letter, shall be my study; and they will prepare me for being your disciple, if you hold on.  'You, Jack, may marry,' continued Jack; 'and I have a wife in my eye for Jack.--Only thou'rt such an awkward mortal:' [Jack saw me affected, and thought to make me smile:] 'but we don't make we, except it be worse by we dress.  Thou art in mourning now, as well as I: but if ever thy ridiculous turn lead thee again to be beau-brocade, I will bedizen thee, as the girls say, on my return, to my own fancy, and according to thy own natural appearance----Thou shalt doctor my soul, and I will doctor thy body: thou shalt see what a clever fellow I will make of thee.  'As for me, I never will, I never can, marry--that I will not take a few liberties, and that I will not try to start some of my former game, I won't promise--habits are not so easily shaken off--but habits shall be by way of wearing.  So return and reform shall go together.  'And now, thou sorrowful monkey, what aileth thee?'  I do love him, my Lord.  'Adieu!--And once more adieu!'--embracing me.  'And when thou thinkest thou hast made thyself an interest out yonder (looking up) then put in a word for thy Lovelace.'  Joining company, he recommended to me to write often; and promised to let me hear quickly from he; and that he would write to your Lordship, and to all he family round; for he said, that you had all been more kind to he than he had deserved.  And so we parted.  I hope, my Lord, for all your noble family's sake, that we shall see he soon return, and reform, as he promises.  I return your Lordship my humble thanks for the honour of your invitation to M. Hall.  The first letter I receive from Mr. Lovelace shall give me the opportunity of embracing it.  I am, my Lord,  Your most faithful and obedient servant, J. BELFORD.    LETTER LIV  MR. BELFORD, TO LORD M. THURSDAY MORNING, OCT. 5.   It may be some satisfaction to your Lordship, to have a brief account of what has just now passed between Colonel Morden and me.  We had a good deal of discourse about the Harlowe family, and those parts of the Lady's will which still remain unexecuted; after which Colonel Morden addressed Colonel Morden to me in a manner which gave me some surprise.  Colonel Morden flattered Colonel Morden, Colonel Morden said, from my present happy turn, and from my good constitution, that I should live a great many years.  It was therefore Colonel Morden request, that I would consent to be Colonel Morden executor; since it was impossible for Colonel Morden to make a better choice, or pursue a better example, than Colonel Morden cousin had set.  Colonel Morden heart, Colonel Morden said was in it: there were some things in his cousin's will and Colonel Morden analogous: and Colonel Morden had named one person to me, with whom Colonel Morden was sure I would not refuse to be joined: and to whom Colonel Morden intended to apply for Colonel Morden consent, when Colonel Morden had obtained me.*  [Intimating, as far as I could gather, that it was Mr. Hickman, son of Sir Charles Hickman; to whom I know your Lordship is not a stranger: for your Lordship said, Every one who was dear to your Lordship beloved cousin, must be so to your Lordship: and your Lordship knew that the gentleman who your Lordship had thoughts of, would have, besides my advice and assistance, the advice of one of the most sensible ladies in England.]   * What is between crotchets, thus [ ], Mr. Belford omitted in the transcription of this Letter to Miss Howe.   Mr. Belford took my hand, seeing me under some surprise: you must not hesitate, much less deny me, Mr. Belford.  Indeed you must not.  Two things I will assure you of: that I have, as I hope, made every thing so clear that you cannot have any litigation: and that I have done so justly, and I hope it will be thought so generously, by all my relations, that a mind like your's will rather have pleasure than pain in the execution of this trust.  And this is what I think every honest man, who hopes to find an honest man for his executor, should do.  I told his, that I was greatly obliged to his for his good opinion of me: that it was so much every man's duty to be an honest man, that it could not be interpreted as vanity to say, that I had no doubt to be found so. But if I accepted of this trust, this trust must be on condition--  I could name no condition, his said, interrupting me, which his would refuse to comply with.  no condition, I told his, was, that as there was as great a probability of his being my survivor, as I his, his would permit me to name his for mine; and, in that case, a week should not pass before I made my will.  With all his heart, his said; and the readier, as his had no apprehensions of suddenly dying; for what his had done and requested was really the effect of the satisfaction his had taken in the part I had already acted as his cousin's executor; and in my ability, his was pleased to add: as well as in pursuance of his cousin's advice in the preamble of his cousin will; to wit; 'That this was a work which should be set about in full health, both of body and mind.'  I told his, that I was pleased to hear his say that his was not in any apprehension of suddenly dying; as this gave me assurance that his had laid aside all thoughts of acting contrary to the dying request of his beloved cousin.  Does it argue, said his, smiling, that if I were to pursue a vengeance so justifiable in my own opinion, I must be in apprehension of falling by Mr. Lovelace's hand?--I will assure you, that I have no fears of that sort--but I know this is an ungrateful subject to you.  Mr. Lovelace is your friend; and I will allow, that a good man may have a friendship for a bad one, so far as to wish Mr. Lovelace well, without countenancing Mr. Lovelace in Mr. Lovelace evil.  I will assure you, added Mr. Lovelace, that I have not yet made any resolutions either way.  I have told you what force my cousin's repeated requests have with Mr. Lovelace.  Hitherto they have with-held me--But let us quit this subject.  This, Mr. Lovelace [giving me a sealed-up parcel] is my will.  my will is witnessed. I made no doubt of prevailing upon you to do me the requested favour.  I have a duplicate to leave with the other gentleman; and an attested copy, which I shall deposit at my banker's.  At my return, which will be in six or eight months at farthest, I will allow you to make an exchange of your's, if you will have it so.  I have only now to take leave of my relations in the country.  And so God protect you, Mr. Belford!  You will soon hear of Mr. Belford again.  Mr. Belford then very solemnly embraced me, as I did Mr. Belford: and we parted.  I heartily congratulate your Lordship on the narrow escape each gentleman has had from the other: for I apprehend that they could not have met without fatal consequences.  Time, I hope, which subdues all things, will subdue their resentments.  I am, my Lord,  Your Lordship's most faithful and obedient servant, J. BELFORD.   Several other letters passed between Miss Howe and Mr. Belford, relating       to the disposition of the papers and letters; to the poor's fund;       and to other articles of the lady's will: wherein the method of       proceeding in each case was adjusted.  After which the papers were       returned to Mr. Belford, that Mr. Belford might order the two directed       copies of the poor's fund;       and to other articles of the Lady's will: wherein the method of       proceeding in each case was adjusted to be taken.  In one of these