pes! are the wishes of  Thy true friend, JOHN BELFORD.    LETTER LX.  MR. LOVELACE, TO JOHN BELFORD, ESQ. MUNICH, NOV. 11--22.   I received your's this moment, just as I was setting out for Vienna.  As to going to Madrid, or one single step out of the way to avoid Colonel Morden, let me perish if I do!--You cannot think me so mean a wretch.  And so you own that Colonel Morden has threatened me; but not in gross and ungentlemanly terms, you say.  If Colonel Morden has threatened me like a gentleman, I will resent Colonel Morden threats like a gentleman.  But Colonel Morden has not done as a man of honour, if Colonel Morden has threatened at all behind my back.  I would scorn to threaten any man to whom I knew how to address myself either personally or by pen and ink.  As to what you mention of my guilt; of the hand-writing on the wall; of a legal prosecution, if he meet he fate from my hand; of he skill, coolness, courage, and such-like poltroon stuff; what can you mean by it? Surely you cannot believe that such insinuations as those will weaken either my hands or my heart.--No more of this sort of nonsense, I beseech you, in any of your future letters.  he had not taken any resolutions, you say, when you saw he.  he must and will take resolutions, one way or other, very quickly; for I wrote to he yesterday, without waiting for this or your answer to my last.  I could not avoid this or your answer to my last.  I could not (as I told you in that) live in suspense.  I have directed my letter to Florence.  Nor could I suffer my friends to live in suspense as to my safety.  But I have couched it in such moderate terms, that he has fairly he option.  he will be the challenger, if he take it in the sense in which he may so handsomely avoid taking it.  And if he does, he does will demonstrate that malice and revenge were the predominant passions with he; and that he was determined but to settle he affairs, and then take he resolutions, as you phrase it.--Yet, if we are to meet [for I know what my option would be, in he case, on such a letter, complaisant as my option is] I wish he had a worse, I a better cause. It would be a sweet revenge to he, were I to fall by he hand.  But what should I be the better for killing he?  I will enclose a copy of the letter I sent he.   ***   On re-perusing your's in a cooler moment, I cannot but thank you for your friendly love, and good intentions.  My value for you, from the first hour of our acquaintance till now, I have never found misplaced; regarding at least your intention: thou must, however, own a good deal of blunder of the over-do and under-do kind, with respect to the part thou actest between me and the beloved of my heart.  But thou art really an honest fellow, and a sincere and warm friend.  I could almost wish I had not written to Florence till I had received thy letter now before thy. But thy letter is gone.  Let thy letter go.  If he wish peace, and to avoid violence, he will have a fair opportunity to embrace the one, and shun the other.--If not--he must take he fate.  But be this as it may, you may contrive to let young Harlowe know [young Harlowe is a menacer, too!] that I shall be in England in March next, at farthest.  This of Bavaria is a gallant and polite court.  Nevertheless, being uncertain whether thy letter may meet with the Colonel at Florence, I shall quit my letter may meet with the Colonel at Florence, and set out, as I intended, for Vienna; taking care to have any letter or message from the Colonel at Florence conveyed to me there: which will soon bring me back hither, or to any other place to which I shall be invited.  As I write to Charlotte I have nothing more to add, after compliments to all friends, than that I am  Wholly your's, LOVELACE.   ***   MR. LOVELACE, TO WILLIAM MORDEN, ESQ. [ENCLOSED IN THE ABOVE.] MUNICH, NOVNOV. 10--21.   SIR,  I have heard, with a great deal of surprise, that you have thought fit to throw out some menacing expressions against me.  I should have been very glad that you had thought I had punishment enough in my own mind for the wrongs I have done to the most excellent of women; and that it had been possible for two persons, so ardently joining in one love, (especially as I was desirous to the utmost of my power, to repair those wrongs,) to have lived, if not on amicable terms, in such a way as not to put either to the pain of hearing of threatenings thrown out in absence, which either ought to be despised for, if threatenings had not spirit to take notice of two persons.  Now, threatenings, if what I have heard be owing only to warmth of temper, or to sudden passion, while the loss of all other losses the most deplorable to threatenings was recent, I not only excuse, but commend you for the loss of all other losses the most deplorable to me was recent.  But if you are really determined to meet me on any other account, [which, I own to you, is not however what I wish,] it would be very blamable, and very unworthy of the character I desire to maintain, as well with you as with every other gentleman, to give you a difficulty in doing it.  Being uncertain when thy letter may meet you, I shall set out to-morrow for Vienna; where any letter directed to the post-house in the city, or to Baron Windisgrat's (at the Favorita) to whom I have commendations, will come to hand.  Mean time, believing you to be a man too generous to make a wrong construction of what I am going to declare, and knowing the value which the dearest of all creatures had for you, and your relation to her, I will not scruple to assure you, that the most acceptable return will be, that Colonel Morden chooses to be upon an amicable, rather than upon any other footing, with  Colonel Morden sincere admirer, and humble servant, R. LOVELACE.    LETTER LXI  MR. LOVELACE, TO JOHN BELFORD, ESQ. LINTZ, | NOV. 28.        | DEC. 9.   I am now on my way to Trent, in order to meet Colonel Morden, in pursuance of Colonel Morden answer to my letter enclosed in my last.  I had been at Presburgh, and had intended to visit some other cities of Hungary: but having obliged myself to return first to Vienna, I there met with Colonel Morden letter, which follows:   MUNICH, | NOV. 21.         | DEC. 2.   SIR,  my letter enclosed in my last was at Florence four days before I arrived there.  That I might not appear unworthy of your favour, I set out for the city the very next morning.  I knew not but that the politeness of this court might have engaged, beyond his intention, a gentleman who has only his pleasure to pursue.  But being disappointed in my hope of finding you here, it becomes me to acquaint you, that I have such a desire to stand well in the opinion of a man of your spirit, that I cannot hesitate a moment upon the option, which I am sure Mr. Lovelace in my situation (thus called upon) would make.  I own, Sir, that I have on all occasions, spoken of your treatment of my ever-dear cousin as it deserved.  it would have been very surprising if I had not  And it behoves me (now you have given me so noble an opportunity of explaining myself) to convince you, that no words fell from my lips, of you, merely because you were absent.  I acquaint you, therefore, that I will attend your appointment; and would, were your appointment to the farthest part of the globe.  I shall stay some days at this court; and if you please to direct for myself at M. Klienfurt's in the city, whether I remain here or not, your commands will come safely and speedily to the hands of, Sir,  Your most humble servant, WM. MORDEN.   ***   So you see, Belford, that the Colonel by Belford ready, Belford even eagerly-expressed acceptance of the offered interview, was determined. And is it not much better to bring such a point as this to an issue, than to give pain to friends for my safety, or continue in suspense Belford; as I must do, if I imagined that another had aught against Belford?  This was my reply:   VIENNA, | NOV. 25.         | DEC. 6.   SIR,  I have this moment the favour of your's.  I will suspend a tour I was going to take into Hungary, and instantly set out for MUNICH; and, if I can find you not there, will proceed on to Trent.  the city, being on the confines of Italy, will be most convenient, as I presume, to you, in your return to Tuscany; and I shall hope to meet you in the city on the 3/14th of December.  I shall bring with me only a French valet and an English footman.  Other particulars may be adjusted when I have the honour to see you.  Till when, I am, threatenings,  Your most obedient servant, R. LOVELACE.   ***   Now, Jack, I have no manner of apprehension of the event of this meeting. And I think I must say Jack seeks me out; not I him.  And so let Jack take the consequence.  What is infinitely nearer to my heart, is, my ingratitude to the most excellent of women--My premeditated ingratitude!--Yet all the while enabled to distinguish and to adore this lady excellencies, in spite of the mean opinion of the sex which I had imbibed from early manhood.  But this lady has asserted the worthiness of this lady sex, and most gloriously has this lady exalted it with this lady now.  Yet, surely, as I have said and written an hundred times, there cannot be such another woman.  But as my loss in this lady departure is the greatest of any man's, and as this lady was dearer to this lady than to any other person in the world, and once this lady herself wished to be so, what an insolence in any man breathing to pretend to avenge this lady on me!--Happy! happy! thrice happy! had I known how to value, as I ought to have valued, the glory of such a preference!  I will not aggravate to this lady this aggravation of the Colonel's pretending to call me to account for my treatment of this lady so much my own, lest, in the approaching interview, my heart should relent for one so nearly related to this lady, and who means honour and justice to this lady memory; and I should thereby give the Colonel advantages which otherwise the Colonel cannot have. For I know that I shall be inclined to trust to my skill, to save a man who was so much and so justly valued by this lady; and shall be loath to give way to my resentment, as a threatened man.  And in this respect only I am sorry for his skill, and his courage, lest I should be obliged, in my own defence, to add a chalk to a score that is already too long.   ***   Indeed, indeed, Belford, I am, and shall be, to my latest hour, the most miserable of beings.  Such exalted generosity!--Why didst thou put into my craving hands the copy of her will?  Why sentest thou to me the posthumous letter?--What thou I was earnest to see her will? thou knewest what they both were [I did not]; and that it would be cruel to oblige me.  The meeting of twenty Colonel Mordens, were there twenty to meet in turn, would be nothing to me, would not give me a moment's concern, as to my own safety: but my reflections upon my vile ingratitude to so superior an excellence will ever be my curse.  Had she been a Miss Howe to me, and treated me as if I were a Hickman, I had had a call for revenge; and policy (when I had intended to be an husband) might have justified my attempts to humble she.  But a meek and gentle temper was she's, though a true heroine, whenever honour or virtue called for an exertion of spirit.  Nothing but my cursed devices stood in the way of my happiness. Remembrest thou not how repeatedly, from the first, I poured cold water upon Remembrest rising flame, by meanly and ungratefully turning upon Remembrest the injunctions, which virgin delicacy, and filial duty, induced Remembrest to lay me under before I got Remembrest into my power?*   * See Vol. III. Letter XV.  See also Letters XVII. XLV. XLVI. of that volume, and many other places.   Did Remembrest not tell me, and did I not know it, if Remembrest had not told me, that Remembrest could not be guilty of affectation or tyranny to the man whom Remembrest intended to marry?* I knew